        {
            "id": "b5afff5c0691492c8d3b5",
            "questionText": "A team of meteorologists is preparing to launch a weather balloon. The balloon is filled with helium with a density of $!$0.178 \\text{ kg/m}^3$!$, and the balloon along with its attached instruments and payload has a mass of $!$5 \\text{ kg}$!$. The balloon has a maximum volume of $!$30 \\text{ m}^3$!$. Calculate the composite density (in $!$\\text{kg/m}^3$!$) of the entire system when the balloon is filled to its maximum volume.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "6e1a30bd3495440482b60",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula needed to calculate the mass of a substance when its density and volume are known. Which one of these formulas do you think is correct?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0bcbc0d9-3537-4386-9a81-b8d3ca195bae"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$m = \\frac{V}{\\rho}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$m = V \\times \\rho$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$m = \\rho - V$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "3a15a17c440343fd9a106",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the formula from the previous step, calculate the mass of helium by multiplying its density by the volume of the balloon. Enter the computed mass of helium.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "5.34"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0bcbc0d9-3537-4386-9a81-b8d3ca195bae"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "2ae04450f59349e380bed",
                    "stepText": "Excellent. Now, add the mass of the payload (which is 5 kg) to the mass of the helium you calculated to obtain the total mass of the system. What is the total mass?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "10.34"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "9fa0a52127594708bedd4",
                    "stepText": "Now, think about how to find the overall density of the system. Which of the following formulas correctly represents the relationship between mass, volume, and density?",
